@stefanpenner like almost every bench out there, they do not perfectly reflect real world use. And I have made that explicit in the post.
@vuejs anyways, I should likely not have ranted as much, but I hope you see my legitimate concerns?
@vuejs I think they serve the purpose in webkit, merely to stress the runtime, but unfortunately not for consumers to make choices.
@stefanpenner why not work with the WebKit committer who wrote these tests to improve them?
@vuejs so, if we where to showcase this, it would again be entirely in-accurate. People would assume ember is insanely fast.

@vuejs so here is the issue, with idiomatic approach. Ember task 87ms to run the entire tests…
@stefanpenner until then you can't prohibit people from drawing their own conclusions.
@stefanpenner I have no intention to mislead people, and I think the best way to battle mis-info is providing better info.
@vuejs the cost of mis-information is high. I would hate for people to be even more confused about an already hard choice.
@vuejs I would not be surprised if there are other massive flaws in the rest of the tests.
@vuejs potentially, but If I have noticed this issues within minutes for 1 framework, I have severe concerns about general mis-information
@stefanpenner sure, would love to have a different, more objective test suite. That would benefit all framework authors.
@vuejs it has nothing really todo with TodoMVC itself but it does with the test suite.
@stefanpenner TodoMVC is not designed in favor of any particular framework, but of course you should take the results with a grain of salt.
@vuejs Not running 100 sequential synchronous run loops.
@stefanpenner you are more than welcome to come up with a more natural test suite.
